Policy_Details: """During Phase I, we can gradually start to reopen economic and social activity. This will be a deliberate process, and is flexible to adapt to the situation. Some communities may be able to reopen at a faster rate, while others may need to continue restrictions to keep the virus from spreading. During Phase I, we should limit our activity and interactions and continue to maintain social distancing and practice good hygiene to protect our neighbors and ourselves.

Citizens who feel sick should stay home!
Continue to practice good hygiene, including:
Washing hands with soap and water, or using hand sanitizer, especially after touching frequently used items or surfaces;
Avoiding touching your face;
Sneezing or coughing into a tissue, or the inside of your elbow; and
Disinfecting frequently used items and surfaces as much as possible.
Avoid socializing in groups that do not readily allow for appropriate physical distancing (receptions, trade shows, etc.). When in public (parks, outdoor recreation spaces, shopping malls, etc.), individuals should maximize physical distance from others.
Minimize travel to the extent possible."""   Source information: https://governor.mo.gov/sites/gov/files/media/pdf/2020/04/Economic-Reopening-Phase-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Currently open: Grocery stores, pharmacies, banks and credit unions, and gas stations are all open.
Restaurants are open for take-out service only.
Stand alone retail operations are open provided they meet required safety and physical distancing guidelines. Indoor and outdoor malls are closed.
Local outdoor recreation activities are open, including many state parks.
Non-emergency medical care, dentist offices and veterinary care are open and operating, provided they meet required safety guidelines.
Local cultural, civic and faith gatherings are allowed for up to 25 people provided physical distancing can be in place.
Local social gatherings over 10 people are prohibited and those under 10 people must use physical distancing.
Personal care services such as salons and barbers, as well as gyms, are closed.
Child care is open under certain restrictions, with priority placements for children of health care workers, first responders, and frontline workers.
Public transit is open under certain restrictions, and must be sanitized often and enforce 3 feet of space between passengers.
Overnight camps are not permitted. Day camps are open with restrictions, including maximum stable groups of 10 or fewer children.
For summer school, limited in-person, small group instruction and/or summer programming is allowed, with certain restrictions.
 Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: All vulnerable Idahoans should continue to self-isolate. Gatherings, both public and private, of less than 10 people, where appropriate physical distancing and precautionary measures are observed can occur. Hair salons open if ability to meet business protocols. Indoor gyms and recreation facilities can open if ability to meet business protocols. Restaurant dining rooms can open once their plans have been submitted for approval by local public health districts. Nightclubs remain closed. Nightclubs should develop plans for reopening as a bar in Stage 3 with ability to meet business protocols and without close contact activities such as dancing. Bars remain closed. Bars should develop plans for reopening and ability to meet business protocols in order to open in stage 3. Large venues (e.g., movie theaters, and sporting venues) are closed. Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://coronavirus.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/stay-healthy-order-stage2.pdf

Policy_Details: This is NOT an SIP/SAH. It is a Public Health Disaster Emergency Proclamation "Today, [5/13/20] Governor Reynolds signed a new proclamation continuing the Public Health Disaster Emergency. The proclamation permits salons, barbershops, and massage and tattoo establishments to reopen throughout Iowa in a limited fashion with appropriate public health measures in place. It also permits restaurants (but not bars), fitness centers, libraries, and race tracks to reopen in the 22 counties where they have remained closed. These changes are effective at 5:00 a.m. on Friday, May 15. The proclamation continues the other ongoing closures and public health measures, including the prohibition on social, community, recreational, leisure, and sporting gatherings and events of more than 10 people, until 11:59 p.m. on May 27, 2020."   Source information: https://governor.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Public%20Health%20Proclamation%20-%202020.05.13.pdf?utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery

Policy_Details: Currently open: Grocery stores, pharmacies, banks and credit unions, and gas stations are all open.
Restaurants are open for take-out service only.
Stand alone retail operations are open provided they meet required safety and physical distancing guidelines. Indoor and outdoor malls are closed.
Local outdoor recreation activities are open, including many state parks.
Non-emergency medical care, dentist offices and veterinary care are open and operating, provided they meet required safety guidelines.
Local cultural, civic and faith gatherings are allowed for up to 25 people provided physical distancing can be in place.
Local social gatherings over 10 people are prohibited and those under 10 people must use physical distancing.
Personal care services such as salons and barbers, as well as gyms, are closed.
Child care is open under certain restrictions, with priority placements for children of health care workers, first responders, and frontline workers.
Public transit is open under certain restrictions, and must be sanitized often and enforce 3 feet of space between passengers.
Overnight camps are not permitted. Day camps are open with restrictions, including maximum stable groups of 10 or fewer children.
For summer school, limited in-person, small group instruction and/or summer programming is allowed, with certain restrictions.
 Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: All businesses and employers are encouraged to adopt and/or take the following actions: Businesses should encourage customers to wear FACE COVERINGS. Continue to encourage TELEWORK, whenever possible and feasible with business operations. If possible, have employees RETURN TO WORK IN PHASES. CLOSE COMMON AREAS where personnel are likely to congregate and interact, or enforce strict social distancing protocols. Follow guidance from the NEVADA LABOR COMMISSIONER regarding sick leave policies. Strongly consider SPECIAL ACCOMMODATIONS for employees who are members of a vulnerable population. Consider encouraging employees to do a SELF-ASSESSMENT each day in order to check if they have any COVID-19 type symptoms (fever, cough or shortness of breath). Remind employees to STAY HOME WHEN SICK, use cough and sneeze etiquette, and practice hand hygiene. Frequently perform enhanced ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING of commonly touched surfaces. Social Distancing & Sanitation Practices in Businesses - All businesses should consider proactive measures to help protect staff and customers, including but not limited to: • Implementing separate operating hours for the elderly and vulnerable customers. • Designating with signage, tape or by other means, six feet of spacing for employees, customers, clients or members to maintain appropriate distance. • Having hand sanitizer, and sanitizing products, readily available for employees and customers.   Source information: https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Declaration-of-Emergency-Directive-018.Phase-1-Reopening.5-7-20-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Carney announced Phase 2 of Delaware's reopening will begin June 15, 2020
INDIVIDUAL GUIDELINES
-Cloth coverings must be worn
-Non-household members must maximize social distancing
-All individuals in public (parks, outdoor recreation areas, shopping, etc) must social distance
-Indoor gathering limit: 50 people but social distance from non-household members
-Places operating at 30% occupancy under Phase 1 can move to 60% occupancy 
-Exercise facilities and personal care services (hair, tanning, tattoo, massage, nail, brow, spas) to remain at 30% occupancy
-Fully unenclosed outdoor gatherings of up to 250 people are permitted
-Leisure travel should be avoided but may resume under general guidance
-All vulnerable individuals should continue to shelter in place
BUSINESS GUIDELINES
-Common areas where people can congregate must remain closed
-Employees/customers have responsibility to self-quarantine if they think they may be sick
-Teleworking is encouraged
-All surfaces touched by customers must be disinfected by EPA-approved disinfectant every 15 minutes to 2 hours 
-Employees required to go to work should perform daily health work 
-All employees must wash hands throughout the day and use hand sanitizer and social distance from other employees
-Businesses must make hand sanitizer available to employees and patrons (hand sanitizer must be 60% ethanol and 70% isopropanol 
-Downtime should be given between shifts and after closing for cleaning

Policy_Details: "During Phase I, we can gradually start to reopen economic and social activity. This will be a deliberate process, and is flexible to adapt to the situation. Some communities may be able to reopen at a faster rate, while others may need to continue restrictions to keep the virus from spreading. During Phase I, we should limit our activity and interactions and continue to maintain social distancing and practice good hygiene to protect our neighbors and ourselves. Citizens who feel sick should stay home! Continue to practice good hygiene, including: Washing hands with soap and water, or using hand sanitizer, especially after touching frequently used items or surfaces; Avoiding touching your face; Sneezing or coughing into a tissue, or the inside of your elbow; and Disinfecting frequently used items and surfaces as much as possible. Avoid socializing in groups that do not readily allow for appropriate physical distancing (receptions, trade shows, etc.). When in public (parks, outdoor recreation spaces, shopping malls, etc.), individuals should maximize physical distance from others. Minimize travel to the extent possible."   Source information: https://governor.mo.gov/sites/gov/files/media/pdf/2020/04/Economic-Reopening-Phase-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Gatherings (planned or spontaneous event, public or private, indoor or outdoor) of more than 50 people are prohibited 
Hotels/motels for lodging purposes, livestock auctions, groups of workers being transported for jobs, government business/facilities, relief facilities, residential buildings, grocery stores, truck stops, retail/business establishments, healthcare facilities, alcohol and drug treatment centers, long term care/assisted living facilities, religious or faith based organizations, funeral homes, parades are exempt from this order
Events not specifically identified by name or type within order may allow indoor and outdoor gatherings of more than 50 people but no more than 250 people (rodeos, speedway motor races, outdoor concerts, sporting events, fairs, track/field races, farmer's markets, firework shows, weddings)
Groups of attendees must be limited to 6 
6ft distance between individual groups
# of people in confined area must be limited to allow for adequate distancing between households
Close contact between members of different households is prohibited before, during, after event
Staff, host/organizers of event, event participants must be screened for symptoms of COVID-19 prior to event 
Entire event facility shall be cleaned thoroughly
Staff who come within 6 ft of event attendees must wear face covering
Face coverings must be worn by individual groups if 6 ft is not possible 
Event shall not take place without appropriate PPE for staff
Encourage contactless and non-signature payment
Signage reminding attendees not to enter if they have symptoms of COVID-19
Participants in sporting events shall not congregate in groups larger than 50 people
 Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://covid19.wyo.gov/governors-orders

Policy_Details: Every individual age 5 and older in Wisconsin must wear a face covering if indoors or in an enclosed space, and if other individuals who do not share living space are present. An "enclosed space" is defined as confined space open to members of the public, including outdoor restaurants and parks. A "face covering" is defined as a material or piece of cloth that completely covers the nose and mouth. Exceptions are included for individuals who are consuming food or beverage; communicating with those hard of hearing; accessing services like dental work where masks must be removed; sleeping; swimming or lifeguarding; presenting to an audience who are physically distanced and wearing masks; engaging in work deemed by government safety guidelines where face coverings pose a personal risk; confirming their identity when accessing financial institutions; present where state or federal law or regulations prohibit face coverings; as well as those individuals who are under the age of 2; have trouble breathing; incapacitated in some manner; incarcerated. Wisconsin State Legislature and Wisconsin Supreme Court facilities are also exempt. Violators are subject to a fine of not more than $200.   Source information: https://evers.wi.gov/Documents/COVID19/EmO01-SeptFaceCoverings.pdf

-Houses of worship may open to 50% occupancy and not to exceed 50 people indoors
-Outdoor worship services can attain approval for maximum numbers of individuals and must maintain 6 ft apart from non-household members
-Face coverings are encouraged to be worn by staff, volunteers, and congregants, unless the person is under 2 years old, has trouble breathing, or those who can't remove a mask without assistance
-Houses of worship must follow guidelines for cleaning and disinfecting their buildings before, during, and after worship 
-   Source information: https://covid19.colorado.gov/covid-19-in-colorado/public-health-executive-orders-resource

Policy_Details: On 7/23 Gov. John Bel Edwards signed Proclamation 96 JBE 2020 extending Phase 2 which also included a mask mandate (face covering must be worn by all, with exceptions, when inside a commercial establishment or any other building or space open to the public, whether indoor or outdoor)
No bar, with or without a food service permit from the Louisiana Department of Health, shall allow for on premises consumption of any food or drinks. However, any bar shall be allowed to provide for takeout through drive-thru or curbside delivery, including alcoholic beverages

Places of public amusement (including but not limited to, locations with amusement rides, carnivals, amusement parks, splash pads, water parks, trampoline parks, arcades, fairs and festivals, children's play centers, indoor playgrounds, theme parks, concert and music halls) to remain closed unless the business submits a reopening plan that must be approved by the State Fire Marshal in consultation with the State Department of Health- occupancy will not exceed 50% in these approved plans (or guidance for opening in phase 3). 

Shopping malls may reopen at no more than 50% of the total occupancy as determined by the State Fire Marshal.
b) Any store or business establishment in a shopping mall may reopen at no more than 50% of the total occupancy as determined by the State Fire Marshal, counting both the number of employees and members of the public present in the building at one time.
c) Mall food courts may open in line with the restaurant guidance 

Casinos, Racetracks, and Video Poker Establishments:
a) No establishment shall exceed 50% of the total occupancy as determined by the State Fire Marshal.
b) No more than 75% of gaming positions shall be in use at anyone time and all utilized gaming positions shall be at least 6 feet apart from one another, unless separated by physical barriers.
c) All establishments shall be required to have approved reopening plans from the Louisiana Gaming Control Board prior to reopening. Further, any plan to use physical barriers needs to be approved by the Louisiana Gaming Control Board.
d) All racetracks shall be required to have an approved reopening plan from the Louisiana Racing Commission prior to reopening.
e) Lobbies or other areas where members of the public may congregate (except for bathrooms) shall be closed to the public. Members of the public should be required to wait outside, while maintaining social distancing, or in vehicles.    Source information: https://gov.louisiana.gov/assets/Proclamations/2020/96-JBE-2020-State-of-Emergency-COVID-19-Resilient-Louisiana-Phase-2.pdf

Policy_Details: Executive order signed by governor, statewide Cooper signed an executive order modifying the stay-at-home order and transitioning the state into Phase 1 of easing restrictions, effective 5:00 p.m. on May 8. The order will last until at least May 22. The modified order removes the distinction between essential and nonessential businesses. Retail businesses may operate at 50% capacity and must implement health and safety measures for workers and customers. Cloth face coverings are recommended for workers, and teleworking is encouraged whenever possible. In Phase 1, restaurants remain limited to drive-through, takeout and delivery service. Bars, personal care businesses, entertainment venues and gyms will stay closed. Child care facilities can be open during Phase 1, subject to strict cleaning protocols, to serve families of parents who are working or looking for work. Summer day camps can operate in compliance with state guidelines. Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://files.nc.gov/governor/documents/files/EO121-Stay-at-Home-Order-3.pdf

Policy_Details: 
-Employees must wear proper face coverings
-Perform frequent hand hygiene (with soap and water or alcohol-based hand sanitizer).1. Restaurants and other licensed food establishments, including taverns, nightclubs, and mixed-use facilities that serve food, may continue to operate with seated outdoor eating and drinking.
- Restaurants and other licensed food establishments may open for indoor dining with the following minimum safeguards:
-All indoor dining/drinking customers must be seated, place orders, and be served at tables;
-. No more than six (6) individuals may be seated indoors at a table or a joined table, and indoor and outdoor fixed tables that accommodate larger groups than are permitted may demarcate six (6) feet between groups and allow seating at those large tables;
- Bar seating is prohibited if any bartender is working at that bar;
- All tables must be placed so that patrons are at least six (6) feet apart;
- All restaurants and licensed food establishments must implement sanitization and disinfection protocols
- Darts, pool, billiards, ping-pong, pinball, playgrounds, and other activities that are not carried out seated at tables are prohibited
- No queuing indoors shall be allowed, and outdoors, patrons must be separated by at least six (6) feet.
- Restaurants and other licensed food establishments may serve customers up to fifty percent (50%) of their maximum capacity
- Restaurants and other licensed food establishments are encouraged to use a reservation system, preferably online or by telephone, to avoid crowding and queuing nearby.-
- Restaurants and other licensed food establishments are encouraged to keep customer logs to facilitate contact tracing if necessary.   Source information: https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/page_content/attachments/COVID-19_DC_Health_Guidance_for_Restaurants_08202020.pdf

Policy_Details: -Employees and patrons must wear a cloth face covering at all times
-Gloves must be worn only as indicated per routine job responsibilities.
•Perform frequent hand hygiene (with soap and water or alcohol-based hand sanitizer).
-Avoid Close Contact and Reduce Touch points for Patrons and Employees(indoor barriers, encourage online shopping, make one way paths etc.)
-Employers must perform screening (e.g., symptom questionnaires) of employees daily,
prior to entering the business, over the phone or in person
-sick employees must not enter workplace ; if sick at work must immediately be separated and sent home.
-Limits the number of persons in the establishment at 50% of occupancy as specified on the Certificate of Occupancy and establishes processes.   Source information: https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/page_content/attachments/COVID-19_DC_Health_Guidance_for_Retail_08202020.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Carney announced Phase 2 of Delaware's reopening will begin June 15, 2020
INDIVIDUAL GUIDELINES
-Cloth coverings must be worn
-Non-household members must maximize social distancing
-All individuals in public (parks, outdoor recreation areas, shopping, etc) must social distance
-Indoor gathering limit: 50 people but social distance from non-household members
-Places operating at 30% occupancy under Phase 1 can move to 60% occupancy 
-Exercise facilities and personal care services (hair, tanning, tattoo, massage, nail, brow, spas) to remain at 30% occupancy
-Fully unenclosed outdoor gatherings of up to 250 people are permitted
-Leisure travel should be avoided but may resume under general guidance
-All vulnerable individuals should continue to shelter in place
BUSINESS GUIDELINES
-Common areas where people can congregate must remain closed
-Employees/customers have responsibility to self-quarantine if they think they may be sick
-Teleworking is encouraged
-All surfaces touched by customers must be disinfected by EPA-approved disinfectant every 15 minutes to 2 hours 
-Employees required to go to work should perform daily health work 
-All employees must wash hands throughout the day and use hand sanitizer and social distance from other employees
-Businesses must make hand sanitizer available to employees and patrons (hand sanitizer must be 60% ethanol and 70% isopropanol 
-Downtime should be given between shifts and after closing for cleaning 
-Employees must post signs about how to stop spread of COVID-19, hand hygiene, and wear a face covering  Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://governor.delaware.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/24/2020/06/Delaware-Economic-Reopening-PHASE-2.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Polis released public health order revising Safer at Home, and in the Vast, Great Outdoors
-Private campgrounds may open and campground operators must regularly clean & disinfect areas
-Group facilities, pavilions, cabins, yurts remain closed
-Campsites must be 6 ft apart, only available by reservation 
-Limit visitors in campground offices to maintain such distancing 
PERSONAL RECREATION 
-Personal recreation (playgrounds, outdoors sports facilities) at a maximum of 25 people 
-Outdoor swimming pools open at 50% occupancy, no more than 50 people 
-Organized recreational youth/adult league sports can start with no more than 25 players outdoors or 10 players indoors, parents can attend youth sports but remain 6 ft apart from non-household members, spectators discouraged at adult sports & sports league must retain records of players in case of later outbreak
-Gyms, recreation centers, indoor pools open at 25% occupancy, not to exceed 50 people, restrooms and showers open but lockers are closed
-Competitive events (races, endurance events) permitted with 6 ft distancing and limit on group size
OUTDOOR RECREATION 
-Outdoor recreation is permitted with non-guided recreation groups no larger than 10 people
-Guide services for fishing, hunting, biking, horseback riding, canoeing, kayaking, stand up paddle boarding, ATV tours, climbing permitted with groups no more than 10 people
-River outfitters, rafting, Jeep tours in groups up to 2 households in a boat or groups of no more than 10 in Jeep
-Developed hot springs may operate following outdoor pool requirements
-Outdoor recreation activities at ski resorts if local public health agency has reviewed & approved resort's plans 
-Outdoor recreation activities not at ski resorts if local public health agency has reviewed & approved plans 
-Scenic trains if every local public health agency in each jurisdiction train operates reviews and approves train's plans 
-Trail and conservation crew no larger than 10    Source information: https://covid19.colorado.gov/covid-19-in-colorado/public-health-executive-orders-resource

Policy_Details: Stay at home order ended by governor on april 30th, statewide. Executive order to enter phase one.  Texas' stay-at-home order ended April 30. Gov. Greg Abbott allowed retail stores, restaurants, movie theaters, malls, and museums to operate at 25% capacity starting May 1, saying businesses should operate with social distancing and sanitation measures in mind. Under Abbott's "Open Texas" plan, personal care businesses such as barbershops, hair salons, and tanning salons were allowed to resume operations starting on May 8. Gyms and exercise facilities, manufacturers, and offices are permitted to reopen on May 18, and must keep social distancing and sanitation requirements in mind. There have been no further announcements of how Texas will further ease restrictions. Public swimming pools, bars, interactive amusement venues, such as bowling alleys, and tattoo parlors remain closed. Policy_Details: New Mexico's stay at home restrictions were modified on April 30, with an extension of the state's stay-at-home order in place until May 15.
New Mexicans must remain home except for outings essential for health, safety and welfare, especially elderly and vulnerable individuals. If you must leave home, gatherings of more than five people remain prohibited and 6 feet of physical distance from others must be maintained.
Large retailers like big-box stores and grocery stores will continue operating at 20 percent capacity as determined by fire code.  
Other high-intensity contact services that must remain closed include indoor malls, massage and tattoo parlors, theaters, casinos.
WHAT WILL CHANGE BEGINNING MAY 16:
All retailers may operate according to COVID-Safe Practices (“CSPs”) at 25 percent fire code occupancy (a “retailer” is any business that sells goods directly to the ultimate consumer or end-users and does not include wholesalers or suppliers, not does it include entertainment venues such as movie theaters, concert halls, or amusement parks);
Non-essential businesses (other than retailers; such as office spaces, call centers) generally may operate according to CSPs at up to 25 percent of pre-crisis staffing levels. All employees should continue to work from home wherever possible;
   Source information: https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/05/13/stay-at-home-order-extended/

Policy_Details: New Mexico's stay at home restrictions were modified on April 30, with an extension of the state's stay-at-home order in place until May 15.
New Mexicans must remain home except for outings essential for health, safety and welfare, especially elderly and vulnerable individuals. If you must leave home, gatherings of more than five people remain prohibited and 6 feet of physical distance from others must be maintained.
Locations and services where high-intensity contact is unavoidable – such as dine-in service at restaurants and bars – will remain temporarily closed. Limited in-person operations for those types of businesses could be included in the next modification of the public health order, as soon as early June, depending on New Mexico’s rate of COVID-19 transmission, testing capacity and other gating criteria.
Other high-intensity contact services that must remain closed include theaters, casinos.   Source information: https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/05/13/stay-at-home-order-extended/

Policy_Details: """During Phase I, we can gradually start to reopen economic and social activity. This will be a deliberate process, and is flexible to adapt to the situation. Some communities may be able to reopen at a faster rate, while others may need to continue restrictions to keep the virus from spreading. During Phase I, we should limit our activity and interactions and continue to maintain social distancing and practice good hygiene to protect our neighbors and ourselves.

Citizens who feel sick should stay home!
Continue to practice good hygiene, including:
Washing hands with soap and water, or using hand sanitizer, especially after touching frequently used items or surfaces;
Avoiding touching your face;
Sneezing or coughing into a tissue, or the inside of your elbow; and
Disinfecting frequently used items and surfaces as much as possible.
Avoid socializing in groups that do not readily allow for appropriate physical distancing (receptions, trade shows, etc.). When in public (parks, outdoor recreation spaces, shopping malls, etc.), individuals should maximize physical distance from others.
Minimize travel to the extent possible."""   Source information: https://governor.mo.gov/sites/gov/files/media/pdf/2020/04/Economic-Reopening-Phase-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Carney announced Phase 2 of Delaware's reopening will begin June 15, 2020
INDIVIDUAL GUIDELINES
-Cloth coverings must be worn
-Non-household members must maximize social distancing
-All individuals in public (parks, outdoor recreation areas, shopping, etc) must social distance
-Indoor gathering limit: 50 people but social distance from non-household members
-Places operating at 30% occupancy under Phase 1 can move to 60% occupancy 
-Exercise facilities and personal care services (hair, tanning, tattoo, massage, nail, brow, spas) to remain at 30% occupancy
-Fully unenclosed outdoor gatherings of up to 250 people are permitted
-Leisure travel should be avoided but may resume under general guidance
-All vulnerable individuals should continue to shelter in place
BUSINESS GUIDELINES
-Common areas where people can congregate must remain closed
-Employees/customers have responsibility to self-quarantine if they think they may be sick
-Teleworking is encouraged
-All surfaces touched by customers must be disinfected by EPA-approved disinfectant every 15 minutes to 2 hours 
-Employees required to go to work should perform daily health work 
-All employees must wash hands throughout the day and use hand sanitizer and social distance from other employees
-Businesses must make hand sanitizer available to employees and patrons (hand sanitizer must be 60% ethanol and 70% isopropanol 
-Downtime should be given between shifts and after closing for cleaning 
-Employees must post signs about how to stop spread of COVID-19, hand hygiene, and wear a face covering  Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://governor.delaware.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/24/2020/06/Delaware-Economic-Reopening-PHASE-2.pdf

Policy_Details: State Health Officer Scott Harris signed 7/15 new Safer at Home Order with face covering requirement as ordered by Governor Kay Ivey's Proclamation from 7/15 effective 7/16 at 5:00pm: all required to wear face coverings when within six feet of a person from another household in any of the following places: an indoor space open to the general public, a vehicle operated by a transportation service, or an outdoor public space where ten or more people are gathered, with exceptions for those age 6 or under, those with relevant medical condition that prevents mask being worn, when eating/drinking, when receiving a service (i.e. personal care) that requires face to be uncovered, for security and safety purposes, when actively exercising or swimming, when essential for effective communication (mouth needs to be visible, or when broadcasting), when voting or attending religious services (strongly encouraged but not required because constitutionally protected activities), when conducting essential job functions for which face covering prevents necessary public safety function (first responders) or is unsafe by industry standards.    Source information: https://governor.alabama.gov/assets/2020/07/Safer-at-Home-Order-Mask-Amendment-7.15.2020-FINAL.pdf

Any local government that decides to impose equal or more stringent restrictions during this phase is permitted to do so, except with regards to essential functions in KEFF. Policy_Details: Currently open: Grocery stores, pharmacies, banks and credit unions, and gas stations are all open.
Restaurants are open for take-out service only.
Stand alone retail operations are open provided they meet required safety and physical distancing guidelines. Indoor and outdoor malls are closed.
Local outdoor recreation activities are open, including many state parks.
Non-emergency medical care, dentist offices and veterinary care are open and operating, provided they meet required safety guidelines.
Local cultural, civic and faith gatherings are allowed for up to 25 people provided physical distancing can be in place.
Local social gatherings over 10 people are prohibited and those under 10 people must use physical distancing.
Personal care services such as salons and barbers, as well as gyms, are closed.
Child care is open under certain restrictions, with priority placements for children of health care workers, first responders, and frontline workers.
Public transit is open under certain restrictions, and must be sanitized often and enforce 3 feet of space between passengers.
Overnight camps are not permitted. Day camps are open with restrictions, including maximum stable groups of 10 or fewer children.
For summer school, limited in-person, small group instruction and/or summer programming is allowed, with certain restrictions.
 Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: "All businesses and employers are encouraged to adopt and/or take the following
actions:
Businesses should encourage customers to wear FACE COVERINGS.
Continue to encourage TELEWORK, whenever possible and feasible with business operations.
If possible, have employees RETURN TO WORK IN PHASES.
CLOSE COMMON AREAS where personnel are likely to congregate and interact, or enforce strict social
distancing protocols.
Follow guidance from the NEVADA LABOR COMMISSIONER regarding sick leave policies.
Strongly consider SPECIAL ACCOMMODATIONS for employees who are members of a vulnerable
population.
Consider encouraging employees to do a SELF-ASSESSMENT each day in order to check if they have
any COVID-19 type symptoms (fever, cough or shortness of breath).
Remind employees to STAY HOME WHEN SICK, use cough and sneeze etiquette, and practice hand
hygiene.
Frequently perform enhanced ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING of commonly touched surfaces.
Social Distancing & Sanitation Practices in Businesses - All businesses should consider proactive
measures to help protect staff and customers, including but not limited to:
• Implementing separate operating hours for the elderly and vulnerable customers.
• Designating with signage, tape or by other means, six feet of spacing for employees, customers,
clients or members to maintain appropriate distance.
• Having hand sanitizer, and sanitizing products, readily available for employees and customers."   Source information: https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Declaration-of-Emergency-Directive-018.Phase-1-Reopening.5-7-20-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Northam issued amended Executive Order 65 easing certain temporary restrictions of businesses
Restaurants, dining establishments, food courts, breweries, microbreweries, distilleries, wineries, and tasting rooms may operate delivery, take out, indoor/outdoor dining, and beverage services in compliance with guidelines
Occupancy may not exceed 50% 
All parties must be limited to 50 patrons or less
Tables at which dining parties are seated must be positioned 6 ft apart
No self service of food (except beverages) and including condiments 
Bar seats must be closed to patrons except for through traffic 
Employees must wear face coverings at all times
Cleaning and disinfection of frequently contacted surfaces must be conducted every 60 minutes
If businesses cannot adhere to these guidelines, they must close  Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/EO-65-and-Order-Of-Public-Health-Emergency-Six---AMENDED---Phase-Two-Easing-of-Certain-Temporary-Restrictions-Due-to-Novel-Coronavirus-(COVID-19).pdf

Policy_Details: Cooper signed an executive order modifying the stay-at-home order and transitioning the state into Phase 1 of easing restrictions, effective 5:00 p.m. on May 8. The order will last until at least May 22.

Retail businesses may operate at 50% capacity and must implement health and safety measures for workers and customers. Cloth face coverings are recommended for workers, and teleworking is encouraged whenever possible.

Policy_Details: " Salons
As of May 4th, beauty/nail salons, barber shops, massage therapy services, and tattoo parlors/studios in the above LHDs will be permitted to open.  These establishments will be added to the list of gatherings subject to the 10-person rule.
The new DHM will require both workers and patrons of these establishments to wear masks.
For districts other than those listed above, these establishments will remain closed past May 3rd.
•       Restaurants
As of May 4th, restaurants will be allowed to serve dine-in customers if all of the following conditions are met:
   The restaurant limits seating to 50% of the rated occupancy maximum at all times.
   The restaurant seats parties at least six feet apart.
   All dining parties are restricted to no more than six persons (groups larger than six will need to sit at separate tables).
   Self-serve buffets and salad bars are prohibited.  Restaurant staff must serve food directly to customers or implement buffet orders from the customer table.  No customer self-service will be allowed.
   Bar seating is not permitted.
   Patrons may only consume alcohol on the premises if also consuming a meal.
Bars that do not serve food will remain limited to carry-out sales and delivery only.
For districts other than those listed above, restaurants will remain limited to delivery, drive-thru, or carryout past May 3rd.

•       Childcare Facilities
 As of May 4th, childcare facilities will be permitted to have up to 15 kids per room/space.
    All other state provisions, statutes, and regulations (including child-to-staff ratios) still apply.
    For districts other than those listed above, childcares will remain restricted to 10 children per room/space.

•       Other Establishments
Bars, gentlemen’s clubs, bottle clubs, indoor movie theaters, indoor theaters/playhouses will remain closed statewide until May 31st, though the State may revise the DHM prior to that date."   Source information: https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/gov-ricketts-announces-upcoming-changes-directed-health-measures-deploys-additional-resources

Policy_Details: This is NOT an SIP/SAH.  It is a Public Health Disaster Emergency Proclamation

"Today, [5/13/20] Governor Reynolds signed a new proclamation continuing the Public Health Disaster Emergency. The proclamation permits salons, barbershops, and massage and tattoo establishments to reopen throughout Iowa in a limited fashion with appropriate public health measures in place. It also permits restaurants (but not bars), fitness centers, libraries, and race tracks to reopen in the 22 counties where they have remained closed. These changes are effective at 5:00 a.m. on Friday, May 15.

The proclamation continues the other ongoing closures and public health measures, including the prohibition on social, community, recreational, leisure, and sporting gatherings and events of more than 10 people, until 11:59 p.m. on May 27, 2020."    Source information: https://governor.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Public%20Health%20Proclamation%20-%202020.05.13.pdf?utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery

Policy_Details: Greg Abbott issued Executive Order No. GA-29 relating to the use of face coverings during the COVID- 19 disaster on July 2. Every person in Texas shall wear a face covering over the nose and mouth when inside a commercial entity or other building or space open to the public, or when in an outdoor public space, wherever it is not feasible to maintain six feet of social distancing from another person not in the same household; provided, however, that this face-covering requirement does not apply to children under 10, medical exemptions/disabilities, when eating, swimming, or exercising (with distance), when driving only with those of same household, for security reasons, and when involved or observing in religious services or assisting or participating in process of voting (but strongly encouraged). Counties with cases under 20 who have opted out of requirement also exempt.   Source information: https://open.texas.gov/uploads/files/organization/opentexas/EO-GA-29-use-of-face-coverings-during-COVID-19-IMAGE-07-02-2020.pdf

Policy_Details: -When leaving their residence or visiting the District, all individuals must continue to maintain a distance of at least six feet from persons not in their household, except if such distance is impossible to maintain (ex: obtaining medical services or salon services)

Policy_Details: New Mexico's stay at home restrictions were modified on April 30, with an extension of the state's stay-at-home order in place until May 15. New Mexicans must remain home except for outings essential for health, safety and welfare, especially elderly and vulnerable individuals. If you must leave home, gatherings of more than five people remain prohibited and 6 feet of physical distance from others must be maintained. Large retailers like big-box stores and grocery stores will continue operating at 20 percent capacity as determined by fire code. Locations and services where high-intensity contact is unavoidable – such as gyms, salons and dine-in service at restaurants and bars – will remain temporarily closed. Limited in-person operations for those types of businesses could be included in the next modification of the public health order, as soon as early June, depending on New Mexico’s rate of COVID-19 transmission, testing capacity and other gating criteria. Other high-intensity contact services that must remain closed include indoor malls, massage and tattoo parlors, theaters, casinos. 14-day quarantine order remains in place for out-of-state airport arrivals. Vacation rentals prohibited to out-of-state residents. Visits to long-term care and other congregate care facilities remain restricted. WHAT WILL CHANGE BEGINNING MAY 16: All retailers may operate according to COVID-Safe Practices (“CSPs”) at 25 percent fire code occupancy (a “retailer” is any business that sells goods directly to the ultimate consumer or end-users and does not include wholesalers or suppliers, not does it include entertainment venues such as movie theaters, concert halls, or amusement parks); Non-essential businesses (other than retailers; such as office spaces, call centers) generally may operate according to CSPs at up to 25 percent of pre-crisis staffing levels. All employees should continue to work from home wherever possible; Houses of worship may operate at 10 percent occupancy; Additional state parks and certain outdoor recreation guides with COVID-Safe Practices; Masks will be required of everyone in public places, with exceptions for eating, drinking and exercising and medical requirements.   Source information: https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/05/13/stay-at-home-order-extended/

Policy_Details:  Salons As of May 4th, beauty/nail salons, barber shops, massage therapy services, and tattoo parlors/studios in the above LHDs will be permitted to open. These establishments will be added to the list of gatherings subject to the 10-person rule. The new DHM will require both workers and patrons of these establishments to wear masks. For districts other than those listed above, these establishments will remain closed past May 3rd. • Restaurants As of May 4th, restaurants will be allowed to serve dine-in customers if all of the following conditions are met: The restaurant limits seating to 50% of the rated occupancy maximum at all times. The restaurant seats parties at least six feet apart. All dining parties are restricted to no more than six persons (groups larger than six will need to sit at separate tables). Self-serve buffets and salad bars are prohibited. Restaurant staff must serve food directly to customers or implement buffet orders from the customer table. No customer self-service will be allowed. Bar seating is not permitted. Patrons may only consume alcohol on the premises if also consuming a meal. Bars that do not serve food will remain limited to carry-out sales and delivery only. For districts other than those listed above, restaurants will remain limited to delivery, drive-thru, or carryout past May 3rd. • Childcare Facilities As of May 4th, childcare facilities will be permitted to have up to 15 kids per room/space. All other state provisions, statutes, and regulations (including child-to-staff ratios) still apply. For districts other than those listed above, childcares will remain restricted to 10 children per room/space. • Other Establishments Bars, gentlemen’s clubs, bottle clubs, indoor movie theaters, indoor theaters/playhouses will remain closed statewide until May 31st, though the State may revise the DHM prior to that date.   Source information: https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/gov-ricketts-announces-upcoming-changes-directed-health-measures-deploys-additional-resources

Policy_Details: Phase 2 of the "Ad Astra" plan. These will be moved to Phase 3; Businesses and activities that will be allowed to open in Phase 2 include: Recreational organized sports facilities, tournaments and practices will be allowed to begin on Friday, May 22, and must adhere to social distancing requirements and follow Parks and Recs guidelines, which can be found on covid.ks.gov; Community Centers will be allowed to open, except for indoor and outdoor swimming pools; Indoor leisure spaces such as arcades, trampoline parks, theaters, museums and bowling allies will be allowed to open on May 22; State-owned-and-operated casinos will be allowed to open once their re-opening plan has been approved by the Kansas Department of Health and Environment; In-person group exercise classes will be allowed to begin with groups of no more than 15 at a time. Locker rooms remain closed except for restroom facilities; Everything opened in Phase 1 and Phase 1.5 remains open pursuant to the restrictions outlined in Executive Order 20-34. Policy_Details: Governor Polis released public health order revising Safer at Home, and in the Vast, Great Outdoors
-Private campgrounds may open and campground operators must regularly clean & disinfect areas
-Group facilities, pavilions, cabins, yurts remain closed
-Campsites must be 6 ft apart, only available by reservation 
-Limit visitors in campground offices to maintain such distancing 
PERSONAL RECREATION 
-Personal recreation (playgrounds, outdoors sports facilities) at a maximum of 25 people 
-Outdoor swimming pools open at 50% occupancy, no more than 50 people 
-Organized recreational youth/adult league sports can start with no more than 25 players outdoors or 10 players indoors, parents can attend youth sports but remain 6 ft apart from non-household members, spectators discouraged at adult sports & sports league must retain records of players in case of later outbreak
-Gyms, recreation centers, indoor pools open at 25% occupancy, not to exceed 50 people, restrooms and showers open but lockers are closed
-Competitive events (races, endurance events) permitted with 6 ft distancing and limit on group size
OUTDOOR RECREATION 
-Outdoor recreation is permitted with non-guided recreation groups no larger than 10 people
-Guide services for fishing, hunting, biking, horseback riding, canoeing, kayaking, stand up paddle boarding, ATV tours, climbing permitted with groups no more than 10 people
-River outfitters, rafting, Jeep tours in groups up to 2 households in a boat or groups of no more than 10 in Jeep
-Developed hot springs may operate following outdoor pool requirements
-Outdoor recreation activities at ski resorts if local public health agency has reviewed & approved resort's plans 
-Outdoor recreation activities not at ski resorts if local public health agency has reviewed & approved plans 
-Scenic trains if every local public health agency in each jurisdiction train operates reviews and approves train's plans 
-Trail and conservation crew no larger than 10    Source information: https://covid19.colorado.gov/covid-19-in-colorado/public-health-executive-orders-resource

Policy_Details: "All businesses and employers are encouraged to adopt and/or take the following
actions:
Businesses should encourage customers to wear FACE COVERINGS.
Continue to encourage TELEWORK, whenever possible and feasible with business operations.
If possible, have employees RETURN TO WORK IN PHASES.
CLOSE COMMON AREAS where personnel are likely to congregate and interact, or enforce strict social
distancing protocols.
Follow guidance from the NEVADA LABOR COMMISSIONER regarding sick leave policies.
Strongly consider SPECIAL ACCOMMODATIONS for employees who are members of a vulnerable
population.
Consider encouraging employees to do a SELF-ASSESSMENT each day in order to check if they have
any COVID-19 type symptoms (fever, cough or shortness of breath).
Remind employees to STAY HOME WHEN SICK, use cough and sneeze etiquette, and practice hand
hygiene.
Frequently perform enhanced ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING of commonly touched surfaces.
Social Distancing & Sanitation Practices in Businesses - All businesses should consider proactive
measures to help protect staff and customers, including but not limited to:
• Implementing separate operating hours for the elderly and vulnerable customers.
• Designating with signage, tape or by other means, six feet of spacing for employees, customers,
clients or members to maintain appropriate distance.
• Having hand sanitizer, and sanitizing products, readily available for employees and customers."   Source information: https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Declaration-of-Emergency-Directive-018.Phase-1-Reopening.5-7-20-1.pdf

Policy_Details: "During Phase I, we can gradually start to reopen economic and social activity. This will be a deliberate process, and is flexible to adapt to the situation. Some communities may be able to reopen at a faster rate, while others may need to continue restrictions to keep the virus from spreading. During Phase I, we should limit our activity and interactions and continue to maintain social distancing and practice good hygiene to protect our neighbors and ourselves. Citizens who feel sick should stay home! Continue to practice good hygiene, including: Washing hands with soap and water, or using hand sanitizer, especially after touching frequently used items or surfaces; Avoiding touching your face; Sneezing or coughing into a tissue, or the inside of your elbow; and Disinfecting frequently used items and surfaces as much as possible. Avoid socializing in groups that do not readily allow for appropriate physical distancing (receptions, trade shows, etc.). When in public (parks, outdoor recreation spaces, shopping malls, etc.), individuals should maximize physical distance from others. Minimize travel to the extent possible."   Source information: https://governor.mo.gov/sites/gov/files/media/pdf/2020/04/Economic-Reopening-Phase-1.pdf

Policy_Details: This is NOT an SIP/SAH. It is a Public Health Disaster Emergency Proclamation "Today, [5/13/20] Governor Reynolds signed a new proclamation continuing the Public Health Disaster Emergency. The proclamation permits salons, barbershops, and massage and tattoo establishments to reopen throughout Iowa in a limited fashion with appropriate public health measures in place. It also permits restaurants (but not bars), fitness centers, libraries, and race tracks to reopen in the 22 counties where they have remained closed. These changes are effective at 5:00 a.m. on Friday, May 15. The proclamation continues the other ongoing closures and public health measures, including the prohibition on social, community, recreational, leisure, and sporting gatherings and events of more than 10 people, until 11:59 p.m. on May 27, 2020." Policy_Details: " Salons
As of May 4th, beauty/nail salons, barber shops, massage therapy services, and tattoo parlors/studios in the above LHDs will be permitted to open.  These establishments will be added to the list of gatherings subject to the 10-person rule.
The new DHM will require both workers and patrons of these establishments to wear masks.
For districts other than those listed above, these establishments will remain closed past May 3rd.
•       Restaurants
As of May 4th, restaurants will be allowed to serve dine-in customers if all of the following conditions are met:
   The restaurant limits seating to 50% of the rated occupancy maximum at all times.
   The restaurant seats parties at least six feet apart.
   All dining parties are restricted to no more than six persons (groups larger than six will need to sit at separate tables).
   Self-serve buffets and salad bars are prohibited.  Restaurant staff must serve food directly to customers or implement buffet orders from the customer table.  No customer self-service will be allowed.
   Bar seating is not permitted.
   Patrons may only consume alcohol on the premises if also consuming a meal.
Bars that do not serve food will remain limited to carry-out sales and delivery only.
For districts other than those listed above, restaurants will remain limited to delivery, drive-thru, or carryout past May 3rd.

•       Childcare Facilities
 As of May 4th, childcare facilities will be permitted to have up to 15 kids per room/space.
    All other state provisions, statutes, and regulations (including child-to-staff ratios) still apply.
    For districts other than those listed above, childcares will remain restricted to 10 children per room/space.

•       Other Establishments
Bars, gentlemen’s clubs, bottle clubs, indoor movie theaters, indoor theaters/playhouses will remain closed statewide until May 31st, though the State may revise the DHM prior to that date."   Source information: https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/gov-ricketts-announces-upcoming-changes-directed-health-measures-deploys-additional-resources

Policy_Details: "All businesses and employers are encouraged to adopt and/or take the following
actions:
Businesses should encourage customers to wear FACE COVERINGS.
Continue to encourage TELEWORK, whenever possible and feasible with business operations.
If possible, have employees RETURN TO WORK IN PHASES.
CLOSE COMMON AREAS where personnel are likely to congregate and interact, or enforce strict social
distancing protocols.
Follow guidance from the NEVADA LABOR COMMISSIONER regarding sick leave policies.
Strongly consider SPECIAL ACCOMMODATIONS for employees who are members of a vulnerable
population.
Consider encouraging employees to do a SELF-ASSESSMENT each day in order to check if they have
any COVID-19 type symptoms (fever, cough or shortness of breath).
Remind employees to STAY HOME WHEN SICK, use cough and sneeze etiquette, and practice hand
hygiene.
Frequently perform enhanced ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING of commonly touched surfaces.
Social Distancing & Sanitation Practices in Businesses - All businesses should consider proactive
measures to help protect staff and customers, including but not limited to:
• Implementing separate operating hours for the elderly and vulnerable customers.
• Designating with signage, tape or by other means, six feet of spacing for employees, customers,
clients or members to maintain appropriate distance.
• Having hand sanitizer, and sanitizing products, readily available for employees and customers."   Source information: https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Declaration-of-Emergency-Directive-018.Phase-1-Reopening.5-7-20-1.pdf

Policy_Details: "Restaurants and bars must:
Ensure tables are spaced at least six (6) feet apart so that at least six (6) feet between parties is maintained, including when customers approach or leave tables
Require all employees to wear cloth face or disposable coverings (provided by the employer)
End all on-site consumption of food and drinks by 10pm      Personal care services (salons, barber shops, massage, etc.) must:
Make appointments with pre-appointment health check
Maintain a customer log
Maintain Six feet physical distancing between clients
Remove all magazines, newspapers, snacks and beverages from waiting areas
Require face coverings by employees and clients (depending on the services provided)     Gyms/ fitness must:
Limit maximum number of customers accordingly
Enforce physical distancing & sanitation"   Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: Currently open: Grocery stores, pharmacies, banks and credit unions, and gas stations are all open.
Restaurants are open for take-out service only.
Stand alone retail operations are open provided they meet required safety and physical distancing guidelines. Indoor and outdoor malls are closed.
Local outdoor recreation activities are open, including many state parks.
Non-emergency medical care, dentist offices and veterinary care are open and operating, provided they meet required safety guidelines.
Local cultural, civic and faith gatherings are allowed for up to 25 people provided physical distancing can be in place.
Local social gatherings over 10 people are prohibited and those under 10 people must use physical distancing.
Personal care services such as salons and barbers, as well as gyms, are closed.
Child care is open under certain restrictions, with priority placements for children of health care workers, first responders, and frontline workers.
Public transit is open under certain restrictions, and must be sanitized often and enforce 3 feet of space between passengers.
Overnight camps are not permitted. Day camps are open with restrictions, including maximum stable groups of 10 or fewer children.
For summer school, limited in-person, small group instruction and/or summer programming is allowed, with certain restrictions.
 Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: Face Coverings Directive Issued July 18, 2020 by Department of Health- The Secretary of Health requires every person in Arkansas to wear a face covering completely over the mouth and nose in all indoor environments, excluding private residences, where they are exposed to non-household members and distancing of six (6) feet or more cannot be assured and in all outdoor settings, excluding private residences, where there is exposure to non-household members, unless there exists ample space of six (6) feet or more to practice physical distancing.  The following shall be exempt from wearing a face covering a. Persons younger than 10 years of age (This requirement shall not supersede any decision by the Secretary of Education, public school district, or private school to require masks for children younger than 10 years of age while attending school); b. Persons with a medical condition or disability that prevents wearing a face covering; c. Persons performing job duties where a six feet distance is not achievable, but a mask is inhibitory to the ability to safely and effectively perform the job duty; d. Persons participating in athletic activities where a six feet distance is not achievable, but a mask is inhibitory to the activity or active exercise; e. Persons consuming food or drink; f. Persons driving alone or with passengers from the driver’s household; g. Persons receiving services that require access to the face for security, surveillance, or other purposes may temporarily remove a face covering while receiving those services; h. Persons voting, assisting voters, serving as poll watchers, or actively performing election administration duties; however, face coverings are strongly encouraged; i. Persons engaged in religious worship activities; however, face coverings are strongly encouraged; j. Persons giving a speech or performance for broadcast or to an audience; however, those persons shall safely distance from nearby individuals; k. Persons in counties where the Department of Health has certified that risk of community transmission of COVID-19 is low. To be considered low risk, the county must not have a newly identified case of COVID-19 for twenty-eight (28) consecutive days, assuming there has been adequate testing in the county   Source information: https://www.healthy.arkansas.gov/images/uploads/pdf/face_covering_directive.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Carney announced Phase 2 of Delaware's reopening will begin June 15, 2020
INDIVIDUAL GUIDELINES
-Cloth coverings must be worn
-Non-household members must maximize social distancing
-All individuals in public (parks, outdoor recreation areas, shopping, etc) must social distance
-Indoor gathering limit: 50 people but social distance from non-household members
-Places operating at 30% occupancy under Phase 1 can move to 60% occupancy 
-Exercise facilities and personal care services (hair, tanning, tattoo, massage, nail, brow, spas) to remain at 30% occupancy
-Fully unenclosed outdoor gatherings of up to 250 people are permitted
-Leisure travel should be avoided but may resume under general guidance
-All vulnerable individuals should continue to shelter in place
BUSINESS GUIDELINES
-Common areas where people can congregate must remain closed
-Employees/customers have responsibility to self-quarantine if they think they may be sick
-Teleworking is encouraged
-All surfaces touched by customers must be disinfected by EPA-approved disinfectant every 15 minutes to 2 hours 
-Employees required to go to work should perform daily health work 
-All employees must wash hands throughout the day and use hand sanitizer and social distance from other employees
-Businesses must make hand sanitizer available to employees and patrons (hand sanitizer must be 60% ethanol and 70% isopropanol 
-Downtime should be given between shifts and after closing for cleaning 
-Employees must post signs about how to stop spread of COVID-19, hand hygiene, and wear a face covering  Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://governor.delaware.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/24/2020/06/Delaware-Economic-Reopening-PHASE-2.pdf

Policy_Details: - Places of worship are encouraged to continue providing virtual services.

- Places of worship may operate with expanded capacity limits. In no event shall attendance at any service exceed 50% of the capacity of the facility or space where the service is occurring as set forth in its Certificate of Occupancy, or 100 persons, whichever is fewer. Groups of persons attending together shall not exceed 10 persons. Each group must be seated at least 6 feet from each other group.

- Places of worship that choose to operate on this limited basis must clean the facility between services and are encouraged to take reservations and assign seats to conform to this requirement and so as to facilitate contact tracing.

- Singing, choirs, all physical touching of others, and the passing or sharing of items pose particular dangers and are discouraged so as to prevent the spread of COVID-19.   Source information: https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/page_content/attachments/COVID-19_DC_Health_%20Guidance_for_Places_of_Worship_08202020.pdf

Policy_Details: """During Phase I, we can gradually start to reopen economic and social activity. This will be a deliberate process, and is flexible to adapt to the situation. Some communities may be able to reopen at a faster rate, while others may need to continue restrictions to keep the virus from spreading. During Phase I, we should limit our activity and interactions and continue to maintain social distancing and practice good hygiene to protect our neighbors and ourselves.

Citizens who feel sick should stay home!
Continue to practice good hygiene, including:
Washing hands with soap and water, or using hand sanitizer, especially after touching frequently used items or surfaces;
Avoiding touching your face;
Sneezing or coughing into a tissue, or the inside of your elbow; and
Disinfecting frequently used items and surfaces as much as possible.
Avoid socializing in groups that do not readily allow for appropriate physical distancing (receptions, trade shows, etc.). When in public (parks, outdoor recreation spaces, shopping malls, etc.), individuals should maximize physical distance from others.
Minimize travel to the extent possible."""   Source information: https://governor.mo.gov/sites/gov/files/media/pdf/2020/04/Economic-Reopening-Phase-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Currently open: Grocery stores, pharmacies, banks and credit unions, and gas stations are all open.
Restaurants are open for take-out service only.
Stand alone retail operations are open provided they meet required safety and physical distancing guidelines. Indoor and outdoor malls are closed.
Local outdoor recreation activities are open, including many state parks.
Non-emergency medical care, dentist offices and veterinary care are open and operating, provided they meet required safety guidelines.
Local cultural, civic and faith gatherings are allowed for up to 25 people provided physical distancing can be in place.
Local social gatherings over 10 people are prohibited and those under 10 people must use physical distancing.
Personal care services such as salons and barbers, as well as gyms, are closed.
Child care is open under certain restrictions, with priority placements for children of health care workers, first responders, and frontline workers.
Public transit is open under certain restrictions, and must be sanitized often and enforce 3 feet of space between passengers.
Overnight camps are not permitted. Day camps are open with restrictions, including maximum stable groups of 10 or fewer children.
For summer school, limited in-person, small group instruction and/or summer programming is allowed, with certain restrictions.
 Phase Level: 1, Phase Details Source information: https://govstatus.egov.com/reopening-oregon#phase1

Policy_Details: *note: "phases" are not really used to describe MS reopening.  Safe Return Order: Executive Order 1492 by Governor Reeves: Gatherings: non-socially distant (within 6 ft) gatherings to be no more than 20 people indoors or 50 people in an outdoor space; socially distant gatherings (w/ 6 ft minimum distance) no more than 50 people indoors or 100 people outdoors. All businesses/nonprofits now allowed to reopen or remain open w/ limitations: (most already allowed to reopen given restrictions in previous orders) but now Executive Order 1478 amended to allow bars that do not serve food to also reopen given limitations of that order (50% capacity, employee screening & PPE, social distancing between parties, etc.) and amended to allow live music in restaurants and bars given 12 ft distance between performers and customers. Healthcare: emergency and elective procedures allowed to continue to be performed (facilities must reserve 25% of capacity for COVID-19 patients) Outdoor Recreational Activities: (had already been widely reopened w/restrictions in previous orders 1473, 1486, 1491, 1480, 1487, no significant changes) Indoor amusement venues (bowling alleys, rollerskating rinks, arcades, playgrounds, etc.): allowed to reopen 50% capacity, group gatherings limited to 20 customers Reception halls and conference centers allowed to reopen to 25% capacity w/social distancing of tables and max 6 to a table Schools: may reopen for in-person instruction (summer school, special ed, tutoring, etc.) State Courts are to be open. All businesses were allowed to reopen, including bars and movie theaters, capacity limits and additional guidelines.  Phase Level: 3, Phase Details Source information: https://governorreeves.ms.gov/wp-content/uploads/Executive-Order-1492-Safer-Return.pdf

Policy_Details: Phase 2 of the "Ad Astra" plan. Phase Level: 2, Phase Details: Mass gatherings of more than 15 individuals will be prohibited; All businesses and activities slated to open during Phase 2 will be allowed, with the exception of bars, night clubs and swimming pools. These will be moved to Phase 3; Businesses and activities that will be allowed to open in Phase 2 include: Recreational organized sports facilities, tournaments and practices will be allowed to begin on Friday, May 22, and must adhere to social distancing requirements and follow Parks and Recs guidelines, which can be found on covid.ks.gov; Community Centers will be allowed to open, except for indoor and outdoor swimming pools; Indoor leisure spaces such as arcades, trampoline parks, theaters, museums and bowling allies will be allowed to open on May 22; State-owned-and-operated casinos will be allowed to open once their re-opening plan has been approved by the Kansas Department of Health and Environment; In-person group exercise classes will be allowed to begin with groups of no more than 15 at a time. Locker rooms remain closed except for restroom facilities; Everything opened in Phase 1 and Phase 1.5 remains open pursuant to the restrictions outlined in Executive Order 20-34. Source information: https://governor.kansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/EO-20-34-Implementing-Phase-2-Executed.pdf

Policy_Details: "All businesses and employers are encouraged to adopt and/or take the following
actions:
Businesses should encourage customers to wear FACE COVERINGS.
Continue to encourage TELEWORK, whenever possible and feasible with business operations.
If possible, have employees RETURN TO WORK IN PHASES.
CLOSE COMMON AREAS where personnel are likely to congregate and interact, or enforce strict social
distancing protocols.
Follow guidance from the NEVADA LABOR COMMISSIONER regarding sick leave policies.
Strongly consider SPECIAL ACCOMMODATIONS for employees who are members of a vulnerable
population.
Consider encouraging employees to do a SELF-ASSESSMENT each day in order to check if they have
any COVID-19 type symptoms (fever, cough or shortness of breath).
Remind employees to STAY HOME WHEN SICK, use cough and sneeze etiquette, and practice hand
hygiene.
Frequently perform enhanced ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING of commonly touched surfaces.
Social Distancing & Sanitation Practices in Businesses - All businesses should consider proactive
measures to help protect staff and customers, including but not limited to:
• Implementing separate operating hours for the elderly and vulnerable customers.
• Designating with signage, tape or by other means, six feet of spacing for employees, customers,
clients or members to maintain appropriate distance.
• Having hand sanitizer, and sanitizing products, readily available for employees and customers."   Source information: https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Declaration-of-Emergency-Directive-018.Phase-1-Reopening.5-7-20-1.pdf

Policy_Details: Governor Brian Kemp signed Executive Order on August 15th to extend/amend the Empowering a Healthy Georgia order for another two weeks since the most recent order from the beginning of August that expired August 15th . Local governments in Georgia previously could not mandate face coverings, as noted in the previous order, but now are able to on a limited basis require them on government property when threshold met in a county (100+ cases per 100,000 people in previous 14 days).  These Local Option Face Covering Requirements should not be applied when eating/drinking, people who are unable to put on and take off a mask without assistance, those with a religious objection, medical reason.  There should not be any fines or penalties against businesses or other entities and there should not be any fines in excess of 50 dollars per person per offense.  The order cannot be enforced at polling places, private property without consent of owner or occupant, or residential property.
Face coverings are otherwise strongly encouraged.   Source information: https://gov.georgia.gov/executive-action/executive-orders/2020-executive-orders

Policy_Details: This is NOT an SIP/SAH.  It is a Public Health Disaster Emergency Proclamation

"Today, [5/13/20] Governor Reynolds signed a new proclamation continuing the Public Health Disaster Emergency. The proclamation permits salons, barbershops, and massage and tattoo establishments to reopen throughout Iowa in a limited fashion with appropriate public health measures in place. It also permits restaurants (but not bars), fitness centers, libraries, and race tracks to reopen in the 22 counties where they have remained closed. These changes are effective at 5:00 a.m. on Friday, May 15.

The proclamation continues the other ongoing closures and public health measures, including the prohibition on social, community, recreational, leisure, and sporting gatherings and events of more than 10 people, until 11:59 p.m. on May 27, 2020."    Source information: https://governor.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Public%20Health%20Proclamation%20-%202020.05.13.pdf?utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery

Policy_Details: Governor lifted two executive orders, statewide. McMaster lifted the order on May 4. Restaurants are now able to resume outdoor customer dining services in line with sanitation and social distancing guidelines. As of May 11, restaurants can choose to reopen for limited dine-in services if they follow state guidelines, including capping indoor occupancy at 50%. Close contact service providers, fitness and exercise centers, commercial gyms — including group exercise classes — and public or commercial pools can open in a limited capacity on May 18. The state has issued general guidelines for close contact service providers, as well as specific guidelines for cosmetology establishments, pools and fitness centers. McMaster lifted restrictions on boating statewide, effective May 8. Daycare facilities are allowed to open. Policy_Details: Gatherings (planned or spontaneous event, public or private, indoor or outdoor) of more than 50 people are prohibited 
Hotels/motels for lodging purposes, livestock auctions, groups of workers being transported for jobs, government business/facilities, relief facilities, residential buildings, grocery stores, truck stops, retail/business establishments, healthcare facilities, alcohol and drug treatment centers, long term care/assisted living facilities, religious or faith based organizations, funeral homes, parades are exempt from this order
Events not specifically identified by name or type within order may allow indoor and outdoor gatherings of more than 50 people but no more than 250 people (rodeos, speedway motor races, outdoor concerts, sporting events, fairs, track/field races, farmer's markets, firework shows, weddings)
Groups of attendees must be limited to 6 
6ft distance between individual groups
# of people in confined area must be limited to allow for adequate distancing between households
Close contact between members of different households is prohibited before, during, after event
Staff, host/organizers of event, event participants must be screened for symptoms of COVID-19 prior to event 
Entire event facility shall be cleaned thoroughly
Staff who come within 6 ft of event attendees must wear face covering
Face coverings must be worn by individual groups if 6 ft is not possible 
Event shall not take place without appropriate PPE for staff
Encourage contactless and non-signature payment
Signage reminding attendees not to enter if they have symptoms of COVID-19
Participants in sporting events shall not congregate in groups larger than 50 people
 Phase Level: 2, Phase Details Source information: https://covid19.wyo.gov/governors-orders

Policy_Details: -Childcare providers must perform a daily health screen for all children and staff entering
the childcare facility. An individual with any of the following symptoms must not enter the
facility,
-If an individual develops any of the symptoms there must be a plan in place for that individual to immediately isolate.
- Must maintain hygiene (provide hand sanitizer, soap, etc)
-Childcare providers should ensure that children and staff at increased risk for experiencing severe illness due to COVID-19 consult with their medical provider before participating in childcare activities. (ex: Cancer, immunocompromised conditions, serious heart conditions, sickle cell disease, and or severe obesity)
-All adults must wear non-medical face coverings or face masks at all times while participating in childcare activities.
-Children 2 years of age or younger must not wear face masks. 
-Children above the age of two years have the option of wearing a face mask based on a
joint decision between the parent and the child’s healthcare provider
-Childcare facilities must notify DC Health if employee or child patient tests Positive for Covid-19. 
- Cleaning and disinfecting must be kept up to date and effectively( surfaces, toys, etc)   Source information: https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/page_content/attachments/COVID-19_DC_Health_Guidance_for-Childcare_2020-08-05.pdf
